<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
This species was collected in the buffer zone of the Cayambe-Coca National Park on the eastern Imbabura and Pichincha provinces (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Geographical distribution of the three new species of Lepanthes microprsartima Tobar &amp; M. J. Gavil. (black hexagon, three collections), Lepanthes caranqui Tobar &amp; Monteros (black triangle, two collections) and Lepanthes oro-lojaensis Tobar &amp; M. F. Lopez (black pentagon, one collection)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574520" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">4</figureCitation>
). The population from Imbabura (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Natural habitat of Lepanthes caranqui A Paramo of La Carboneria in east of Imbabura province B El Chalpar Area east of Pichincha province. Photographs by F. Tobar and M. Monteros." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574529" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">13</figureCitation>
) grows in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="páramo">paramo</normalizedToken>
(AsSn01) according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Ministerio del Ambiente del Ecuador" journalOrPublisher="Novon" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" publicationUrl="https://www.ambiente.gob.ec/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2012/09/LEYENDA-ECOSISTEMAS_ECUADOR_2.pdf" refId="B16" refString="Ministerio del Ambiente del Ecuador, 2013. Sistema de Clasificacion de los Ecosistemas del Ecuador Continental. Subsecretaria de Patrimonio Natural, 300 pp. https://www.ambiente.gob.ec/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2012/09/LEYENDA-ECOSISTEMAS_ECUADOR_2.pdf" title="Sistema de Clasificacion de los Ecosistemas del Ecuador Continental. Subsecretaria de Patrimonio Natural, 300 pp." url="https://www.ambiente.gob.ec/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2012/09/LEYENDA-ECOSISTEMAS_ECUADOR_2.pdf" year="2013">Ministerio del Ambiente del Ecuador (2013)</bibRefCitation>
as small groups or isolated individuals that grow on roadside embankments along with other members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindl. ex G.Don" authorityYear="1839" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Pleurothallidinae">Pleurothallidinae</taxonomicName>
like 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Draconanthes" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Draconanthes aberrans" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aberrans">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Draconanthes aberrans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Schltr.) Luer, 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Stelis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stelis pusilla" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Stelis pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. lamellata" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="lamellata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">S. lamellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lindl., 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Pleurothallis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pleurothallis bivalvis" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bivalvis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Pleurothallis bivalvis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lindl. and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. apopsis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="apopsis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">P. apopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Luer. The specimens collected in Pichincha grew in evergreen montane forest (BsAn01)(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Natural habitat of Lepanthes caranqui A Paramo of La Carboneria in east of Imbabura province B El Chalpar Area east of Pichincha province. Photographs by F. Tobar and M. Monteros." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574529" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">13</figureCitation>
) according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Ministerio del Ambiente del Ecuador" journalOrPublisher="Novon" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" publicationUrl="https://www.ambiente.gob.ec/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2012/09/LEYENDA-ECOSISTEMAS_ECUADOR_2.pdf" refId="B16" refString="Ministerio del Ambiente del Ecuador, 2013. Sistema de Clasificacion de los Ecosistemas del Ecuador Continental. Subsecretaria de Patrimonio Natural, 300 pp. https://www.ambiente.gob.ec/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2012/09/LEYENDA-ECOSISTEMAS_ECUADOR_2.pdf" title="Sistema de Clasificacion de los Ecosistemas del Ecuador Continental. Subsecretaria de Patrimonio Natural, 300 pp." url="https://www.ambiente.gob.ec/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2012/09/LEYENDA-ECOSISTEMAS_ECUADOR_2.pdf" year="2013">Ministerio del Ambiente del Ecuador (2013)</bibRefCitation>
, and unlike the Imbabura population, the plants grow epiphytically at the base of the trunks or on the lower branches of the trees, where they also share their habitat with 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Stelis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stelis pusilla" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Stelis pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. lamellata" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="lamellata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">S. lamellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Pleurothallis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pleurothallis bivalvis" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bivalvis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Pleurothallis bivalvis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. apopsis" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="apopsis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">P. apopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">The species has been found in flowers and with fruits at different stages of maturity from May to July, suggesting that reproduction takes place all year round.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">The specific epithet honors the Caranqui culture that historically occupied the same areas where this species is distributed.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="preliminary conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Preliminary conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tobar &amp; Monteros" authorityYear="2021" class="Aves" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepanthes caranqui" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caranqui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Lepanthes caranqui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from two localities within an extent of occurrence of 575 km2. It inhabits both paramo and montane forest where it is more abundant, forming small colonies on tree trunks. Its habitat is not considered to be under pressure since it is located in the buffer zone of a protected area but a potential threat would be the advance of the agricultural frontier. However, it has been observed that this orchid can adapt to moderately disturbed areas and is able to colonize different types of vegetation. Considering the abundant number of mature individuals observed in the field we estimate an approximate number of 500 mature individual and giving that its area of occupancy, habitat quality and the number of mature individuals are not declining we suggest the Least Concern (LC) category following the 
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="University of Goeteborg, Stockholm" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" publicationUrl="https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/10315" refId="B8" refString="IUCN, 2012. IUCN red list categories and criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge. https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/10315" title="IUCN red list categories and criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge." url="https://portals.iucn.org/library/node/10315" year="2012">IUCN (2012)</bibRefCitation>
Red List Categories and Criteria.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tobar &amp; Monteros" authorityYear="2021" class="Aves" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Lepanthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lepanthes caranqui" order="Asparagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caranqui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Lepanthes caranqui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically most similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. pachychila" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="pachychila">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. pachychila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Comparison with the most similar species to Lepanthes caranqui Tobar &amp; Monteros A Lepanthes caranqui B Lepanthes pachychila C Lepanthes chrysina D Lepanthes ballatrix. Photographs by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574528" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">12b</figureCitation>
) from the southwest of Ecuador, it differs in having taller plants, petals narrowly triangular-oblong, the lip blade thick, broadly ovate with rounded ends, appendix triangular in the dorsal view, with two protuberances on the top and a minute tuft of hairs at the base. The new species also resembles 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. ballatrix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="ballatrix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. ballatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Comparison with the most similar species to Lepanthes caranqui Tobar &amp; Monteros A Lepanthes caranqui B Lepanthes pachychila C Lepanthes chrysina D Lepanthes ballatrix. Photographs by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574528" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">12c</figureCitation>
) which is widespread in Ecuador and Colombia and 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. chrysina" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="chrysina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. chrysina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Comparison with the most similar species to Lepanthes caranqui Tobar &amp; Monteros A Lepanthes caranqui B Lepanthes pachychila C Lepanthes chrysina D Lepanthes ballatrix. Photographs by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.180.62671.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/574528" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">12d</figureCitation>
) endemic from the southwest of Ecuador. Both species have a triangular, acute dorsal sepal (vs. broadly-ovate, narrowly acuminate). The petal lobes in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. ballatrix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="ballatrix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. ballatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are suborbicular to broadly elliptical, and in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. chrysina" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="chrysina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. chrysina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the upper lobe is oblong, obtuse and the lower obliquely triangular (vs. petals equal, narrowly triangular-oblong in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. caranqui" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="caranqui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. caranqui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the lip blades is glabrous in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. chrysina" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="chrysina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. chrysina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and minutely pubescent in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. ballatrix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="ballatrix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. ballatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. caranqui" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="caranqui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. caranqui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and are oblong lunate in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. ballatrix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="ballatrix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. ballatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and ovate-oblong in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. chrysina" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="chrysina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. chrysina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. caranqui" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="caranqui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. caranqui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The appendix in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. caranqui" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="caranqui">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. caranqui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is triangular pubescent with two protuberances on the top, and in 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. ballatrix" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" rank="species" species="ballatrix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">L. ballatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is triangular, minutely pubescent, thickened at the end, with a pair of minute finger like process.
</paragraph>
